# Baseline List for Time-Series Modality Imputation

Goal: modality-level imputation in time series (recover a missing modality stream from remaining modalities), with fair and reproducible comparisons.

## Reproduction Order (Top to Bottom)

1. PSW-I (ICLR 2025)
- Why first: strong recent time-series imputation baseline with public code and relatively stable training.
- Task alignment: medium (primarily missing-value imputation, not strictly whole-modality missing).
- Role in your paper: primary baseline (time-series imputation family).
- Notes for adaptation: add modality-mask protocol so one full modality can be hidden per sample/time window.

2. Global-IB (NeurIPS 2025)
- Why second: recent strong TS imputation model with good competitiveness.
- Task alignment: medium (general TS imputation; not explicitly modality-level by default).
- Role in your paper: primary baseline (time-series imputation family).
- Notes for adaptation: evaluate both random-feature missing and modality-level missing to show transfer gap.

3. KPI (NeurIPS 2025)
- Why third: another competitive modern imputation baseline to avoid single-method bias.
- Task alignment: medium (general missing-data imputation, weakly modality-specific).
- Role in your paper: primary/secondary baseline depending on adaptation quality.
- Notes for adaptation: keep architecture unchanged; only change missingness generator and input mask interface.

4. Diffusion-TS (ICLR 2024)
- Why fourth: diffusion generator baseline adapted to imputation gives a strong generative reference.
- Task alignment: medium-low (native task is generation, not modality imputation).
- Role in your paper: secondary baseline (adapted generator).
- Notes for adaptation: convert to conditional generation with observed modalities as condition; evaluate imputation metrics only.

5. ImagenTime (NeurIPS 2024)
- Why fifth: complementary generation-style model; useful robustness check.
- Task alignment: medium-low (generation-first model).
- Role in your paper: secondary baseline (adapted generator).
- Notes for adaptation: same adaptation policy as Diffusion-TS; avoid over-tuning.

6. IMDer (NeurIPS 2023)
- Why sixth: representative missing-modality method with public code.
- Task alignment: medium-low (incomplete multimodal emotion recognition, not pure TS modality imputation).
- Role in your paper: cross-domain missing-modality baseline.
- Notes for adaptation: keep original objective where possible; clearly mark task mismatch in table footnote.

7. MD2N (ICCV 2025)
- Why seventh: recent missing-modality method; useful as broad multimodal recovery reference.
- Task alignment: medium-low (evaluated on MOSI/MOSEI MER settings).
- Role in your paper: cross-domain missing-modality baseline.
- Notes for adaptation: if no official code remains unavailable, report as "paper-reference" or reimplement only core module with explicit disclaimer.

## Optional "Closer" Baselines (If Time Allows)

8. VIMTS (BigData 2022)
- Task alignment: relatively high for multimodal time-series imputation.
- Caveat: engineering friction and ecosystem maturity may be lower.

9. TSEst / attention-based multimodal imputation (SDM 2023)
- Task alignment: medium-high (multimodal support), but protocol details should be checked carefully.

## Protocol Rules (Must Keep Constant Across Baselines)

- Missingness setups:
  - Whole-modality missing (core): hide 1 modality entirely for a sample or for contiguous windows.
  - Random missing (auxiliary): feature-level random masks for compatibility with TS imputation baselines.
- Same splits, same preprocessing, same normalization.
- Same evaluation seeds and repeat count.
- Report both:
  - Imputation quality (e.g., MAE/RMSE/CRPS depending on your setting)
  - Downstream utility (if you use a downstream task)

## Execution Plan You Can Follow Directly

- Phase A (must): PSW-I -> Global-IB -> KPI
- Phase B (should): Diffusion-TS -> ImagenTime
- Phase C (cross-domain): IMDer -> MD2N
- Phase D (optional): VIMTS / TSEst

This ordering maximizes fairness first (time-series imputation), then breadth (generation adaptation), then cross-domain comparison (missing-modality multimodal learning).
